[[File:Sogatsuhiko-jinja, torii.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii gate}}]]
'''Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine''' (そがにますそがつひこじんじゃ<ref>[http://www.narashinsei.com/search/%E3%82%B5%E8%A1%8C/%E5%AE%97%E6%88%91%E5%9D%90%E5%AE%97%E6%88%91%E9%83%BD%E6%AF%94%E5%8F%A4%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE/ Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine] (Nara Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines).</ref>/そがにいますそがつひこじんじや{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}/そがのそがつひこじんじゃ{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} located in Soga-chō, {{ill|lt=Kashihara City|Q496319|WD=Q496319}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN}} (major shrine), and under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284}}.

It is also commonly known as “Iruka-no-miya.” The shrine is known as being associated with the ancient powerful clan, the {{ill|lt=Soga clan|Q909854|WD=Q909854}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The enshrined deities are the following two {{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}:
:* '''Sogatsuhiko-no-Kami''' (そがつひこのかみ, also written 宗我都比古神)
:* '''Sogatsuhime-no-Kami''' (そがつひめのかみ, also written 宗我都比売神)

In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Register of Deities}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470}}), the shrine is listed as having two seats of deities. The entry records the name as “Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine,” meaning “the shrine that enshrines Sogatsuhiko in Soga (= Soga/Soga/Soga: a place name).” One of the two seats is identified as Sogatsuhiko-no-Kami, but the identity of the other seat is unclear.

=== About the enshrined deities ===
<div class="thumb tright">
 <div style="margin: 0px; padding: 2px; border: 1px solid #a2a9b1; text-align: center; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; text-align:center; font-size:80%">
'''Genealogy of the {{ill|lt=Soga clan|Q909854|WD=Q909854}}'''
{{familytree/start|style="text-align:left; font-size:100%"}}
{{familytree|border=0||||,|-|.||,|.}}
{{familytree|border=0|01|!|02|!|03| 01={{Supra|8th}}{{ill|lt=Emperor Kōgen|Q333572|WD=Q333572}}|02={{ill|lt=Soga Ishikawa|Q11625205|WD=Q11625205}}|03={{ill|lt=Soga Iname|Q595897|WD=Q595897|lt=Iname}}}}
{{familytree|border=0|||!|!||!||!|!}}
{{familytree|border=0|01|!|02|!|03| 01={{ill|lt=Hikofuto-oshi no Mikoto|Q11487911|WD=Q11487911}}|02={{ill|lt=Soga Manchi|Q11251684|WD=Q11251684|lt=Manchi}}|03={{ill|lt=Soga no Umako|Q1191233|WD=Q1191233|lt=Umako}}}}
{{familytree|border=0|||!|!||!||!|!}}
{{familytree|border=0|01|!|02|!|03| 01={{ill|lt=Yanu-oshi-o Takeo-gokoro no Mikoto|Q11465637|WD=Q11465637}}<br />{{Small|(Not in Kojiki)}}|02={{ill|lt=Soga Kaneko|Q11625210|WD=Q11625210|lt=Kaneko}}|03={{ill|lt=Soga no Emishi|Q1292368|WD=Q1292368|lt=Emishi}}}}
{{familytree|border=0|||!|!||!||!|!}}
{{familytree|border=0|01|!|02|!|03| 01={{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668}}|02={{ill|lt=Soga Koma|Q1092497|WD=Q1092497|lt=Koma}}|03={{ill|lt=Soga no Iruka|Q736621|WD=Q736621|lt=Iruka}}}}
{{familytree|border=0|||`|'||`|-|'}}
{{familytree/end}}
</div></div>

Because the shrine name and deity name include “Sogatsuhiko,” the ritual practices of Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine are thought to be connected to the ancient powerful {{ill|lt=Soga clan|Q909854|WD=Q909854}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}. Although the Soga clan is a well-known lineage, its original homeland ({{ill|lt=honkan|Q846706|WD=Q846706}}) has not been definitively identified. Three main theories are known: that it was located in Soga (the area around present-day Soga-chō, Kashihara City) in {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495}} {{ill|lt=Takaichi District|Q1117901|WD=Q1117901}} (the site of this shrine); that it was in {{ill|lt=Katsuge District|Q11620858|WD=Q11620858}} of Yamato Province (around present-day {{ill|lt=Gose City|Q847334|WD=Q847334}}); or that it was in {{ill|lt=Ishikawa District, Kawachi Province|Q11586399|WD=Q11586399}} (the eastern half of {{ill|lt=Tondabayashi City|Q490928|WD=Q490928}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723}}, and the {{ill|lt=Minamikawachi District|Q1347323|WD=Q1347323}} area){{Sfn|Soga clan (ancient clans)|2010}}{{Sfn|Soga (encyclopedia of ancient clans)|2015}}. Among these, the first theory (this area) is considered particularly persuasive, based on the place name “Soga,” the presence of Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine, and a passage in the *Kishi Kachō* that states of {{ill|lt=Soga Ishikawa|Q11625205|WD=Q11625205|lt=Soga Ishikawa no Sukune}}: “Residence: Soga village, Takaichi district, Yamato Province”{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}{{Sfn|Soga clan (ancient clans)|2010}}{{Sfn|Soga (encyclopedia of ancient clans)|2015}}.

As mentioned above, the *Engishiki* Jinmyōchō lists two seats of deities. Regarding this, the *Gogun Jinjaki* assigns them to {{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668}} and {{ill|lt=Soga Ishikawa|Q11625205|WD=Q11625205|lt=Ishikawa no Sukune}}, while shrine records from around the {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001}} era ({{ill|lt=1688|Q7671|WD=Q7671}}–{{ill|lt=1704|Q6824|WD=Q6824}}) assign them to {{ill|lt=Hikofuto-oshi no Mikoto|Q11487911|WD=Q11487911}} and Ishikawa no Sukune{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}. In all cases, these figures are regarded as distant ancestors of the Soga clan. In contrast, the present practice enshrines the two deities Sogatsuhiko and Sogatsuhime, with their two wooden statues worshipped as the {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}. In the Jinmyōchō, many shrines list two seats with the pattern “place name + tsu + hiko/hime,” and in the case of Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine as well, it is considered appropriate to view the enshrined deities as the two local tutelary gods Sogatsuhiko and Sogatsuhime{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine Two Seats (Shikinaisha)|1982}}.

=== History ===
[[File:Sogatsuhiko-jinja, honden.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Main sanctuary}}]]
=== Founding ===
The date of founding is unknown. According to the *Gogun Jinjaki*, during the reign of {{ill|lt=Empress Suiko|Q298057|WD=Q298057}} (r. {{ill|lt=593|Q33889|WD=Q33889}}–{{ill|lt=628|Q30592|WD=Q30592}}), {{ill|lt=Soga no Umako|Q1191233|WD=Q1191233}} built a shrine in Soga village to enshrine {{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668}} and {{ill|lt=Soga Ishikawa|Q11625205|WD=Q11625205|lt=Ishikawa no Sukune}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}. On the other hand, shrine tradition holds that {{ill|lt=Empress Jitō|Q232026|WD=Q232026}} (r. {{ill|lt=690|Q23472|WD=Q23472}}–{{ill|lt=697|Q23489|WD=Q23489}}), lamenting the downfall of the Soga clan, allowed Tokunaga Naigu, the second son of {{ill|lt=Soga no Kurayamada no Ishikawa no Maro|Q3488899|WD=Q3488899}}, to succeed the {{ill|lt=Kii clan|Q11605075|WD=Q11605075}}, and granted land to Naigu’s son Nagasue so that he might enshrine the ancestral deities and carry out shrine duties and cultivation; this event is regarded as the founding of the shrine{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}.

It is also known that the area around Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine encompasses the Nakazoshi site, an archaeological site with remains from the {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|WD=Q207858}} through the early {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|WD=Q459939}}, and many artifacts have been unearthed in and around the shrine grounds<ref>[http://www.city.kashihara.nara.jp/kankou/own_bunkazai/bunkazai/spot/nakazoshi.html Nakazoshi Site] (Kashihara City website “Kashihara Exploration Guide”).</ref><ref>“Nakazoshi Site,” *Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei 30: Place Names of Nara Prefecture*, Heibonsha, 1981.</ref>.

=== Overview ===
According to a document from {{ill|lt=Daidō|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|lt=Daidō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021}}) in the *{{ill|lt=Shinshō Kakuchokufushō|Q11502312|WD=Q11502312}}*, the “Soga deity” at that time was assigned three households from {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495}} as {{ill|lt=shrine households|Q11589711|WD=Q11589711}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}. Based on this record, there is also a theory that one of the 39 shrines in Yamato Province listed as having shrine households in the *Ōyamato no kuni shōzeichō* of {{ill|lt=Tenpyō|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|lt=Tenpyō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=730|Q23563|WD=Q23563}}) corresponds to this shrine{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Six National Histories|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168}}, there are records of Sogatsuhiko-no-Kami being promoted in rank to Junior Fifth Rank, Upper, in {{ill|lt=Ten’an|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten’an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897}}), and to Senior Fifth Rank, Lower, in {{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan}} 6 ({{ill|lt=864|Q25041|WD=Q25041}}){{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}.

In the *Engishiki* Jinmyōchō compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470}}), the shrine is listed in Takaichi District, Yamato Province, as “Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine, two seats, both major; receiving offerings at the Tsukinami and Niiname festivals,” indicating that its two seats were ranked as a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha (major shrine)|Q134917288|WD=Q134917288}} and that it received offerings from the court at the {{ill|lt=Tsukinami Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161}} and {{ill|lt=Niiname Festival|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}.

According to the *Yamato-shi*, during the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718}} it was known as “Iruka-no-miya”{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine (Kami-gami)|2000}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707}}, in September {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096}} 40), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284}} under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534}}{{Sfn|Soga-ni-masu Sogatsuhiko Shrine Two Seats (Shikinaisha)|1982}}.

=== Divine ranks ===
* {{ill|lt=Ten’an|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten’an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897}}) {{ill|lt=January 27|Q2284|WD=Q2284}}: Promoted from Junior Fifth Rank, Lower to Junior Fifth Rank, Upper (*{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981}}*) – recorded as “Sogatsuhiko-no-Kami.”
* {{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan}} 6 ({{ill|lt=864|Q25041|WD=Q25041}}) {{ill|lt=June 16|Q2653|WD=Q2653}}: Promoted from Junior Fifth Rank, Upper to Senior Fifth Rank, Lower (*Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku*) – recorded as “Sogatsuhiko-no-Kami.”

